1
00:00:00,050 --> 00:00:05,877
You're listening to: Designing Async, Long-Running APIs for AI Agents.

2
00:00:05,877 --> 00:00:12,860
AI agents kick off tasks that run for minutes — synchronous request/response breaks down fast.

3
00:00:12,860 --> 00:00:24,314
A practical guide to the async job pattern: 202 + status URLs, polling vs webhooks vs streaming, durable queues, and idempotent resumption.

4
00:00:24,314 --> 00:00:25,336
Let's get started.

5
00:00:25,336 --> 00:00:32,872
The synchronous request/response model has one quiet assumption: the work finishes before the connection times out.

6
00:00:32,872 --> 00:00:36,141
AI agents break that assumption constantly.

7
00:00:36,141 --> 00:00:48,774
An agent asks your backend to "research this topic," "generate this report," or "run this multi-step workflow," and the honest answer takes 30 seconds, two minutes, sometimes more.

8
00:00:48,774 --> 00:00:56,911
Hold the HTTP connection open that long and you'll hit gateway timeouts, blocked worker threads, and lost work on every deploy.

9
00:00:56,911 --> 00:01:02,740
The fix is an old pattern made newly essential: the asynchronous job API.

10
00:01:02,740 --> 00:01:11,694
This is the practical guide to building one for agent clients — it complements the reliability foundations in building backends for AI agents.

11
00:01:11,694 --> 00:01:14,795
Now, let's talk about Why synchronous breaks for agents.

12
00:01:14,795 --> 00:01:16,490
Three forces converge:

13
00:01:16,490 --> 00:01:17,764
Long tasks.

14
00:01:17,764 --> 00:01:26,706
Agent work (research, generation, orchestration) routinely exceeds typical 30–60s gateway timeouts..

15
00:01:26,706 --> 00:01:28,233
Blocked resources.

16
00:01:28,233 --> 00:01:34,062
A request held open for two minutes ties up a worker/connection the whole time.

17
00:01:34,062 --> 00:01:40,192
A burst of agent calls exhausts your pool — the same way a cache stampede exhausts a connection pool..

18
00:01:40,192 --> 00:01:41,622
Lost work on failure.

19
00:01:41,622 --> 00:01:48,425
If the task lives only inside the request handler, a crash or deploy mid-request loses everything.

20
00:01:48,425 --> 00:01:53,016
Agents then retry, and now you're doing the expensive work twice..

21
00:01:53,016 --> 00:01:56,947
The answer is to decouple starting the work from getting the result.

22
00:01:56,947 --> 00:02:01,718
Moving on to The core pattern: 202 + a status resource.

23
00:02:01,718 --> 00:02:06,887
Instead of one blocking call, split it into three cheap, fast interactions:

24
00:02:06,887 --> 00:02:07,680
Start.

25
00:02:07,680 --> 00:02:14,146
POST /jobs → returns 202 Accepted immediately with a job ID and a status URL.

26
00:02:14,146 --> 00:02:16,346
The work is enqueued, not done..

27
00:02:16,346 --> 00:02:17,091
Check.

28
00:02:17,091 --> 00:02:28,569
GET /jobs/{id} → returns pending / running / succeeded / failed, plus progress and (when done) the result or a result URL..

29
00:02:28,569 --> 00:02:29,471
Retrieve.

30
00:02:29,471 --> 00:02:33,064
The result is in the status response or at a linked URL..

31
00:02:33,064 --> 00:02:38,341
Note the idempotency key on start — covered in idempotency keys.

32
00:02:38,341 --> 00:02:44,555
Agents retry the POST, and without it a flaky network spawns five identical two-minute jobs.

33
00:02:44,555 --> 00:02:47,223
With it, retries return the same job.

34
00:02:47,223 --> 00:02:50,012
Next up: How does the agent learn the result?

35
00:02:50,012 --> 00:02:51,225
Three options.

36
00:02:51,225 --> 00:02:53,677
1. Polling (start here).

37
00:02:53,677 --> 00:02:58,834
The agent calls GET /jobs/{id} on an interval until it's done.

38
00:02:58,834 --> 00:03:02,752
Simple, firewall-friendly, and works for every client.

39
00:03:02,752 --> 00:03:05,120
The cost is wasted requests.

40
00:03:05,120 --> 00:03:07,355
Tame it with guidance and backoff:

41
00:03:07,355 --> 00:03:11,310
Return a Retry-After header so the client knows how long to wait..

42
00:03:11,310 --> 00:03:16,959
Suggest exponential backoff (1s, 2s, 4s…) rather than tight polling..

43
00:03:16,959 --> 00:03:24,711
For most agent integrations, polling is the right default — it's the least that can go wrong, and agents are perfectly happy to poll.

44
00:03:24,711 --> 00:03:27,728
2. Webhooks (push, for efficiency).

45
00:03:27,728 --> 00:03:32,788
The caller registers a callback URL; you POST the result when the job finishes.

46
00:03:32,788 --> 00:03:35,661
No wasted polls, near-instant delivery.

47
00:03:35,661 --> 00:03:49,759
The costs are real, though: the receiver needs a public endpoint, and you must treat your own webhook as an at-least-once delivery — sign it, retry on failure with backoff, and make the receiver idempotent (it may arrive twice).

48
00:03:49,759 --> 00:03:54,435
Webhooks shine for server-to-server agents that run their own infrastructure.

49
00:03:54,435 --> 00:03:57,427
3. Streaming (for incremental output).

50
00:03:57,427 --> 00:04:06,057
When the agent benefits from partial results — tokens of a generation, steps of a research run — stream with SSE or a WebSocket.

51
00:04:06,057 --> 00:04:09,038
This is great UX for "show your work" tasks.

52
00:04:09,038 --> 00:04:18,353
The trade-off is that a held-open stream reintroduces some of the resource cost you were escaping, so use it for genuinely incremental output, not as a default.

53
00:04:18,353 --> 00:04:20,024
(WebSocket patterns here.)

54
00:04:20,024 --> 00:04:22,656
Mechanism, Best for, Watch out for.

55
00:04:22,656 --> 00:04:28,221
Polling, Default; any client, Wasted requests (mitigate with backoff).

56
00:04:28,221 --> 00:04:34,507
Webhooks, Server-side agents, Needs public endpoint; at-least-once → idempotent receiver.

57
00:04:34,507 --> 00:04:38,605
Streaming, Incremental output, Held-open connection cost.

58
00:04:38,605 --> 00:04:43,617
Let's explore Behind the API: durable queues, not background threads.

59
00:04:43,610 --> 00:04:45,855
The endpoint is the easy half.

60
00:04:45,855 --> 00:04:49,040
The hard requirement is that the work survives a crash.

61
00:04:49,040 --> 00:04:57,454
Do not run a two-minute task in a fire-and-forget thread inside your web process — a deploy kills it and the job is silently lost.

62
00:04:57,454 --> 00:05:09,629
Instead, enqueue jobs to a durable queue (a real broker, or a jobs table polled by workers — the trade-offs are in message queues: RabbitMQ vs Redis vs Kafka).

63
00:05:09,629 --> 00:05:10,807
Properties you want:

64
00:05:10,807 --> 00:05:11,877
Durability.

65
00:05:11,877 --> 00:05:15,194
A job persists until a worker acknowledges completion..

66
00:05:15,194 --> 00:05:17,069
Retries with a dead-letter queue.

67
00:05:17,069 --> 00:05:28,103
A failing job retries a bounded number of times, then parks in a DLQ for inspection — exactly the discipline that saved a partition in the Kafka consumer-lag war story..

68
00:05:28,103 --> 00:05:29,906
Idempotent processing.

69
00:05:29,906 --> 00:05:37,574
A redelivered job must not double its side effects — persist status transitions and guard the side effects with the action key..

70
00:05:37,574 --> 00:05:48,427
Model the job's lifecycle as durable state — ideally an append-only log of enqueued → running → succeeded/failed — so you can resume, audit, and report progress.

71
00:05:48,427 --> 00:05:52,358
That's the same event-driven backbone agent runs want anyway.

72
00:05:52,358 --> 00:05:55,855
Now let's look at Don't forget cancellation and TTLs.

73
00:05:55,855 --> 00:05:59,052
Agents change their minds and abandon tasks.

74
00:05:59,052 --> 00:06:11,889
Give them DELETE /jobs/{id} to cancel, have workers check a cancellation flag at safe points, and expire finished jobs after a TTL so your store doesn't grow forever.

75
00:06:11,889 --> 00:06:16,132
Small touches, but they're what separate a toy from something an agent can lean on.

76
00:06:16,132 --> 00:06:18,235
Now, let's talk about The takeaway.

77
00:06:18,235 --> 00:06:25,531
Long-running agent work needs the backend to say "I've got it, here's where to check" — not to hold a connection hostage for two minutes.

78
00:06:25,531 --> 00:06:38,151
The async job pattern (202 + status resource), an idempotent start, a durable queue with retries and a DLQ, and a sane result-delivery mechanism is the whole recipe.

79
00:06:38,151 --> 00:06:44,858
It's not new — it's how robust systems have always handled slow work — but agents have made it table stakes.

80
00:06:44,858 --> 00:06:50,002
Build it once and every long tool your agents call gets reliable for free.

81
